<speak version="1.0" xml:lang="en-US" xmlns:mstts="http://www.w3.org/2001/mstts">
  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="0%" pitch="+0st">

  
    <p>Welcome to our lesson on Time Series Analysis and Forecasting.</p>
    <p>First, let's define time series data.</p>
    <p>Time series data consists of observations collected at regular intervals.</p>
    <p>Its main components are trend, seasonality, and noise.</p>
    <p>For example, stock prices, weather patterns, and sales figures are all time series data.</p>
    <break time="400ms"/>
    <p>Next, we will explore the concepts of trend and seasonality.</p>
    <p>Trend refers to the long-term movement in the data, while seasonality indicates regular patterns that repeat over time.</p>
    <p>Visualizing these components can be done effectively using plots.</p>
    <break time="400ms"/>
    <p>Now, let's introduce ARIMA models.</p>
    <p>ARIMA stands for Autoregressive Integrated Moving Average.</p>
    <p>It consists of three components: AR, I, and MA.</p>
    <p>To determine the order of an ARIMA model, we use ACF and PACF plots.</p>
    <break time="400ms"/>
    <p>Next, we will fit an ARIMA model.</p>
    <p>This involves using a sample dataset in Python or R.</p>
    <p>After fitting the model, we evaluate its performance through residual analysis and AIC or BIC criteria.</p>
    <break time="400ms"/>
    <p>Once we have our model, we can generate forecasts.</p>
    <p>It's important to include confidence intervals to understand the uncertainty in our forecasts.</p>
    <break time="400ms"/>
    <p>Finally, we will evaluate forecast accuracy.</p>
    <p>Common metrics include MAE, RMSE, and MAPE.</p>
    <p>We will apply these metrics to assess the ARIMA model's performance on a test dataset.</p>
    <break time="400ms"/>
    <p>Thank you for joining this lesson on Time Series Analysis and Forecasting.</p>
  
    </prosody>
  </voice>
</speak>